  "prompt": "Where can someone find a free good virtual piano keyboard that displays the music sheets upon the keyboard?",
  "response": "Finding a completely free virtual piano keyboard that also displays the corresponding sheet music on the keyboard is a bit of a unicorn. That's because combining these two features requires significant development effort, and most tools with that level of sophistication come with a price tag.\n\nHowever, here's a breakdown of some options that come close and might satisfy your needs, along with strategies to combine different resources:\n\n**Options That Get Close (Combinations Needed):**\n\n1.  **Online Virtual Keyboards + Separate Sheet Music Websites/Software:**\n\n    *   **Online Virtual Keyboards (Focus on responsiveness and sound quality):**\n        *   **OnlinePianist:** (Not entirely free, but offers many free lessons)\n            *   Features interactive piano tutorials, many of which include on-screen keyboard and notation.  The free portion is limited, but it's a good starting point for beginners.\n        *   **Virtual Piano:**  (virtualpiano.net)\n            *   A popular option with a reasonable sound and responsive keyboard. No sheet music directly, but the 'letters' displayed on the keys can be helpful for learning.\n        *   **Apkhubs Virtual Piano:** (apkhubs.com/virtual-piano/)\n            *   A simple online piano with a decent sound.\n    *   **Free Sheet Music Resources:**\n        *   **IMSLP (Petrucci Music Library):** (imslp.org)\n            *   A vast public domain library of sheet music.  You'll need to search for your desired piece.\n        *   **MuseScore:** (musescore.com)\n            *   Has a large library of free user-submitted scores.  You can also use their software (described below) to create your own.\n        *   **Free-scores.com:** (free-scores.com)\n            *   Another large repository of free sheet music.\n    *   **How to Combine:**  Open the virtual piano in one browser tab or window, and the sheet music in another.  This is the most common and readily available method.  You'll need to coordinate between the displayed sheet music and the notes you play on the virtual keyboard.\n\n2.  **Free Music Notation Software + a MIDI Keyboard (if you have one):**\n\n    *   **MuseScore (Software):** (musescore.org)\n        *   A powerful, completely free, open-source music notation program.  It's like a free version of Sibelius or Finale.\n        *   **Key Feature:** You can input notes into MuseScore, and then play them back *using your computer's keyboard as a MIDI input* or a connected MIDI keyboard.\n        *   While MuseScore doesn't *directly* display the sheet music *on* a virtual piano, the notes you play are simultaneously displayed on the staff in real-time.  This is arguably better than having the notes just on the piano keys because you're learning to read the actual notation.\n    *   **Other Free Notation Software:**  LilyPond, Denemo (more advanced, steeper learning curve).\n\n**Why It's Difficult to Find a Perfect Free Solution:**\n\n*   **Complexity:** Combining a responsive, good-sounding virtual piano with real-time sheet music display is a complex programming task.\n*   **Licensing:**  Displaying sheet music often involves copyright issues.  Free resources tend to rely on public domain music or user-submitted content.\n*   **Development Costs:**  Creating and maintaining such a tool requires time, resources, and expertise.  Developers often need to monetize their work to continue supporting it.\n\n**Recommendations:**\n\n*   **Start with the Online Keyboard + Sheet Music Combination:** This is the easiest to get started with immediately. Use Virtual Piano or OnlinePianist for the keyboard and IMSLP or MuseScore for sheet music.\n*   **If You Want to Learn Notation, Use MuseScore:**  Even if you don't have a MIDI keyboard, learning to input notes and play them back through your computer's keyboard is a valuable skill. It will dramatically improve your understanding of music theory and notation. If you *do* have a MIDI keyboard, MuseScore becomes an incredibly powerful tool.\n*   **Consider a Trial of a Paid Option:** Many paid software packages offer free trials.  This will give you a taste of what a fully integrated solution can offer.  Examples include:\n    *   Flowkey\n    *   Synthesia\n\n**In summary, while a *single, completely free* solution that perfectly combines a virtual piano with sheet music display is hard to find, using a combination of free online resources and/or free notation software like MuseScore is a very viable and cost-effective way to learn and play piano.**\n",
